Jennifer Gidley:

"I am using the underused term proflection as a future-oriented contrast to reflection. Reflect  was first used as a verb in 1402 from Latin flectere “to bend” meaning “to bend back” or “turn back” the sun and not until two hundred years later in the sense of "to turn one's thoughts (back)"–first attested 1605. In honor of Gebser’s sense of time concretion, my proflection means, “to turn one’s thought forward.” [http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=reflection&searchmode=none]."

(https://www.academia.edu/197841/The_Evolution_of_Consciousness_as_a_Planetary_Imperative_An_Integration_of_Integral_Views)

